-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. THREE CANDIDATE LAYOUTS
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Option A — Parallel HashMaps per scalar
  e.g. faction_belief: HashMap<u32,u64>, faction_unrest: HashMap<u32,u64>, …
  (+ existing faction_treasury, faction_resources)

  Determinism: UNSAFE unless every consumer sorts keys before iteration or only
    does order-independent reductions. Today engine already sorts for diplomacy;
    easy to miss a new callsite. Serde: N fields with #[serde(default)] — save
    files can have key-set drift between maps (treasury has id 2, belief missing).
  Cache: Poor — updating belief+unrest+cohesion for one polity touches 3+ hash
    buckets scattered in memory.
  Migration: Lowest diff from current treasury pattern — but compounds the
    parallel-HashMap sprawl already present.
  Verdict: AVOID as end state. Acceptable only as a 1-tick dual-write shim.

Option B — Single struct map: BTreeMap<u32, PolityMacroState>
  One row per polity; stable ascending key iteration for free.

  Determinism: STRONG — BTreeMap iteration order is key-sorted; matches
    civ-diplomacy, cluster_stocks, CIV-0105 HiddenNetwork conventions.
  Cache: Good for whole-polity tick passes (one contiguous struct per key);
    poor if hot path is single-scalar random access (still fine for N≤32).
  Serde: One #[serde(default)] map; row presence = polity exists; nested struct
    serializes atomically; missing polities simply absent from save.
  Migration: Natural fold of faction_treasury + faction_resources + new scalars;
    can keep legacy HashMaps as deprecated aliases during transition.
  Verdict: RECOMMENDED primary container.

Option C — SoA arrays indexed by dense PolityIndex
  PolityRegistry { id_to_idx: BTreeMap<u32, u16>, ids: Vec<u32> }
  macro_rows: Vec<PolityMacroState>   // idx → state
  // or parallel Vec<u64> belief, Vec<u64> unrest, …

  Determinism: STRONG if all scans are 0..len and registry built from sorted ids.
  Cache: BEST for uniform per-tick updates across all polities (phase_unrest loop).
  Serde: Vec serializes in index order — must persist id_to_idx alongside or embed
    id inside each row; realign on load if ids sparse.
  Migration: Heavier — must unify with faction_doctrines Vec indexing (today
    assumes faction_id == usize for 0..2); emergent new faction ids break dense
    assumption without registry compaction.
  Verdict: OPTIMIZATION PATH after Option B stabilizes; not first landing.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. RECOMMENDATION (ONE)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Adopt Option B: BTreeMap<u32, PolityMacroState> in WorldState.

Justification (ranked):
  1. Determinism: Eliminates sort_unstable boilerplate at every faction scan;
     aligns with civ-diplomacy BTreeMap policy and engine BTreeMap precedents.
  2. Serde / save safety: Single map = single source of truth; no cross-map key
     drift; #[serde(default)] on one field keeps old saves loadable while globals
     remain as fallback readers during dual-write phase.
  3. Cache: For expected polity counts (3–32), struct-per-row in BTreeMap is
     sufficient; SoA wins only when N≫100 and every tick touches every scalar.
  4. Shadow readiness: CIV-0105 HiddenNetwork is a fat nested object — nests
     cleanly in PolityMacroState; SoA would split graph from scalars awkwardly.
  5. Migration: Incremental — add map beside existing HashMaps, dual-write, switch
     readers, deprecate globals, fold treasury HashMaps into rows last.

Do NOT use HashMap for the struct map (even Option B with HashMap) — repo already
pays sort tax to fix HashMap nondeterminism; BTreeMap is the local convention for
persistent sim state keyed by ids.

Future densification: if profiling shows polity loops hot, add
  fn polity_idx(&self, id: u32) -> Option<usize>
  fn macro_rows(&self) -> &[PolityMacroState]
built from BTreeMap values cached each tick — migrate to Option C without changing
on-wire save shape (still serialize BTreeMap or Vec<PolityMacroState> with id field).

